[[Major-General]] '''Abdullah Saeed''' was a [[Pakistani]] General<ref name="auto">Defence Journal (Pakistan) 2012, Volume 16, Issue 2, Pg.1</ref> who served as Commandant of the [[Kakul Military Academy|Pakistan Military Academy]] at [[Kakul]], [[Chief Martial Law Administrator]] for [[Baluchistan]] when Zia overthrew [[Bhutto, Zulfiqar Ali|Bhutto]] and later [[Pakistan]]'s ambassador to [[Mexico]] and [[Cuba]] under [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref>Defence Journal (Pakistan) 2012, Volume 16, Issue 2, Pg.2</ref><ref>Frontline (India) Volume 25; Issue 21, October 11–24, 2008 pg.1-2</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1094957|title=A leaf from history: Zia’s planned precision|first=Shaikh|last=Aziz|date=23 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref>
==Early career== Abdullah started his career in 6 Frontier Force (FF) Regiment after he graduated the Pakistan Military Academy (PMA) course in 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defencejournal.com/july98/thewayitwas1.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061140/http://www.defencejournal.com/july98/thewayitwas1.htm |archivedate=2016-03-04 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c_VUBQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA308&ots=YZLbdYf95f&dq=Major-General+Abdullah+Saeed&pg=PA308#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=India Pakistan Wars-1947 to 1971-A Strategic and Operational Analysis|first=Agha Humayun|last=Amin|publisher=|via=Google Books}}</ref>
==Personal life== He was born in [[Abottabad]] in the [[Hazara Division|Hazara region]] of the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] province. He was the son of [[Lahore Ahmadiyya Movement]] Emir [[Dr. Saeed Ahmad Khan]] and died in 1988 of [[Colon Cancer]].<ref name="auto"/> [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]] personally went and offered condolences to his family in [[Lahore]].
